    <fr:title text="Structural sheaf on a general open">Structural sheaf on a general open</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any distributive lattice <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, we use <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> to denote the open set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_I]]></fr:tex> via <fr:link href="/idem-comm-HLDT/" title="Frame of opens of spectra" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-HLDT/" display-uri="idem-comm-HLDT" /></fr:link>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{D}(I) \cong  D_I]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  By the sheaf condition, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{D}(I)]]></fr:tex> is the following equaliser,
  
  <html:figure><fr:resource hash="e3fd1b8471c13076bf30652b422c6972"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/e3fd1b8471c13076bf30652b422c6972.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
    \begin {tikzcd}
      \mathcal  O_{D}(I) \ar [r, tail] & \prod _{p\in  I} D/p \ar [r, shift left] \ar [r, shift right] & \prod _{p,q\in  I} D/p\wedge  q
    \end {tikzcd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>

  Hence, an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in \mathcal {O}_{D}(I)]]></fr:tex> is exactly a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u : I \to  D]]></fr:tex> such that
  <html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(i) \le  i]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\in  I]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
    <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u(i) \wedge  j = u(i \wedge  j)]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i,j\in  I]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol>
  This gives an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>-element, since for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  D]]></fr:tex>,
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ u(i \wedge  a) = u(i \wedge  i \wedge  a) = u(i) \wedge  i \wedge  a = u(i) \wedge  a. ]]></fr:tex>
  On the other hand, it suffices to show an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>-element is always contractive. But this is easy, since
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ u(i) = u(i \wedge  i) = u(i) \wedge  i. ]]></fr:tex>
  Hence, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{D}(I)]]></fr:tex> is the set of all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>-elements of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
