                <fr:uri>https://charloced.github.io/schm-ZBG1/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>schm-ZBG1</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/schm-ZBG1/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Structural sheaf is a sheaf for Zariski topology">Structural sheaf is a sheaf for Zariski topology</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>proposition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{D}]]></fr:tex> is a sheaf of distributive lattices on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, which is <fr:link href="/idem-comm-75C1/" title="Local distributive lattice" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-75C1/" display-uri="idem-comm-75C1" type="local">local</fr:link> as an internal distributive lattice.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  We verify the sheaf condition. Again since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p \cong  \operatorname {Spec} D/p]]></fr:tex>, we only need to verify the sheaf condition on the total space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>. By compactness, let us consider a finite union
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ \operatorname {Spec} D = \bigcup _{i\le  n}O_{p_i} = O_{\bigvee _{i\le  n}p_i}, ]]></fr:tex>
  which is equivalent to the fact that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigvee _{i\le  n}p_i = 1]]></fr:tex>. Now suppose we have a compatible family of elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q_i \in  D_{p_i}]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>. Compatibility means
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ q_i \wedge  p_j = q_j \wedge  p_i, ]]></fr:tex>
  for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i,j\le  n]]></fr:tex>. This way, we construct the element
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ q := \bigvee _{i\le  n} q_i. ]]></fr:tex>
  Firstly, indeed we have
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ q \wedge  p_j = \bigvee _{i\le  n}q_i \wedge  p_j = \bigvee _{i\le  n} q_j \wedge  p_i = q_j \wedge  \bigvee _{i\le  n}p_i = q_j. ]]></fr:tex>
  Thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> is indeed an amalgamation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{q_i\}_{i\le  n}]]></fr:tex>. For uniqueness, suppose we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q']]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q' \wedge  p_i = q_i]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>. Then we have
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ q' = \bigvee _{i\le  n} q' \wedge  p_i = \bigvee _{i\le  n} q \wedge  p_i = q. ]]></fr:tex>
  Hence, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{D}]]></fr:tex> is a sheaf. It is local as an internal distributive lattice because at each point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex>, the stalk by <fr:link href="/schm-B6QO/" title="Stalk for structural sheaf" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-B6QO/" display-uri="schm-B6QO" type="local">Remark <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-B6QO/" display-uri="schm-B6QO" /></fr:link> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}_{D,x} \cong  D/x]]></fr:tex>, thus local.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
