            <fr:title text="Frame of opens of spectra">Frame of opens of spectra</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  There is a bijection of frame of opens of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> with the frame <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Idl}(D)]]></fr:tex> of ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. For any ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, the open subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_I]]></fr:tex> it corresponds to is
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ O_I := \{x\in \operatorname {Spec} D\mid \exists  p \in  I.\  x \models  p\} = \bigcup _{p\in  I}O_p. ]]></fr:tex></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  For simplicity, we construct a dual equivalence between closed sets and ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. By construction, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_p]]></fr:tex> be the complement of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[O_p]]></fr:tex>, then the closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_I]]></fr:tex> corresponding to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is given by 
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ C_I = \overline {O_I} = \bigcap _{p\in  I}C_p. ]]></fr:tex>
  On the other hand, given any closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> we construct an ideal
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ I_C := \{p\in  D\mid \forall  x\in  C.\ x \not \models  p\}. ]]></fr:tex>
  Verification is routine.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
